```python
def grad(x): return 2*(x-4)
def descend(lr, steps=20, x=0.0):
    for _ in range(steps): x -= lr*grad(x)
    return x

print(descend(0.1))   # ~4.0  (converges)
print(descend(1.1))   # diverges to huge magnitude
```

With lr=0.1 it homes in on x=4 (the minimum). With lr=1.1 each step *overshoots* by more than it corrects, so x oscillates with growing amplitude and blows up. This is the learning-rate knife-edge that every real training run has to tune — too small wastes steps, too large diverges.
